%S A393842 0,0,0,36,20700,1219980,22557444,226534448,1541819664,7987574700,
%T A393842 33772336620,121971280068,388337820156,1115146224192,2937930504600,
%U A393842 7195155414720,16550399415872,36052378870824,74874652364520,149079454738500,285885011579580,530089977388356,953530399550652,1668722947632048,2848193275290000
%N A393842 Number of n X n binary matrices with exactly 12 1's such that there are an even number of 1's in every row and column.
%C A393842 Also weight A_12 of the weight distribution for a square n X n Single Parity Check Product Code (SPCP) code when the 1's represent bit errors, and 0's represent unchanged data bits. For SPCP code, A_odd = 0, A_4 = C(n,2)^2 = A000537(n-1), A_6 = 3!*C(n,3)^2 = A179058(n), A_8 = A396317(n), A_10 = A396321(n). See the rectangular formula for other message data formats.
%D A393842 E. R. Berlekamp, Algebraic Coding Theory, McGraw-Hill, New York, 1968, pp. 397-400.
%D A393842 R. E. Blahut, Theory and Practice of Error Control Codes, Addison-Wesley, 1983, p. 431.
%D A393842 C. Leung, Evaluation of the Error Probability of Single Parity-Check Codes, IEEE Transactions on Communications Vol. COM-31, NO. 2, Feb 1983, pp. 250-253.
%D A393842 F. J. MacWilliams and N. J. A. Sloane The Theory of Error Correcting Codes, Elsevier/North Holland 1977, p. 21.
%D A393842 W. W. Peterson and E. J. Weldon, Error Correcting Codes, MIT Press, 1994, pp. 64-70, pp. 131-132.
%H A393842 G. Gordon Thompson, <a href="/A393842/b393842.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..500</a>
%H A393842 A. M. Patel, <a href="https://mirrors.meulie.net/bitsavers.org/pdf/ibm/IBM_Journal_of_Research_and_Development/186/ibmrd1806Q.pdf">Optimal Rectangular Code for High Density Magnetic Tapes</a>.
%H A393842 G. Gordon Thompson, <a href="/A396317/a396317_2.pdf">Probability of Undetected Error for Some Simple Product Codes</a>, MS Thesis, UT Arlington TX, May 1984, pp. 35-37.
%H A393842 G. Gordon Thompson, <a href="/A393842/a393842_1.jpg">Diagram of Subsets for 12 1's</a>.
%H A393842 G. Gordon Thompson, <a href="/A393842/a393842.txt">Program For Coefficients of Subsets</a>.
%H A393842 <a href="/index/Rec#order_13">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (13,-78,286,-715,1287,-1716,1716,-1287,715,-286,78,-13,1).
%F A393842 a(n) = 67950*C(n,6)^2 + 70200*C(n,6)*C(n,5) + 10260*C(n,6)*C(n,4) + 360*C(n,6)*C(n,3) + 2*C(n,6)*C(n,2) + 11400*C(n,5)^2 + 1680*C(n,5)*C(n,4) + 36*C(n,4)^2.
%F A393842 The rectangular formula for the n X k matrices is a(n,k) = 67950*C(n,6)*C(k,6) + 35100*C(n,6)*C(k,5) + 35100*C(n,5)*C(k,6) + 5130*C(n,6)*C(k,4) + 5130*C(n,4)*C(k,6) + 180*C(n,6)*C(k,3) + 180*C(n,3)*C(k,6) + C(n,6)*C(k,2) + C(n,2)*C(k,6) + 11400*C(n,5)*C(k,5) + 840*C(n,5)*C(k,4) + 840*C(n,4)*C(k,5) + 36*C(n,4)*C(k,4). Rectangular formula in table form, each entry is multiplied by its top row header and its left column header, then all are summed for a(n,k). The square case, n X n, is n = k.
%F A393842   A_12    C(k,2) C(k,3) C(k,4) C(k,5)  C(k,6).
%F A393842   C(n,2)     0      0       0      0       1.
%F A393842   C(n,3)     0      0       0      0     180.
%F A393842   C(n,4)     0      0      36    840    5130.
%F A393842   C(n,5)     0      0     840  11400   35100.
%F A393842   C(n,6)     1    180    5130  35100   67950.
%F A393842 From _Jianing Song_, Jul 15 2026: (Start)
%F A393842 a(n) = n^2*(n - 1)^2*(n - 2)*(n - 3)*(755*n^6 - 12685*n^5 + 87575*n^4 - 319075*n^3 + 649678*n^2 - 702952*n + 316240)/5760.
%F A393842 G.f.: 4*x^4*(9 + 5058*x + 238422*x^2 + 2075502*x^3 + 5637914*x^4 + 5548090*x^5 + 1970901*x^6 + 216202*x^7 + 4352*x^8)/(1 - x)^13.
%F A393842 E.g.f.: x^4*(8640 + 984960*x + 8770560*x^2 + 16515456*x^3 + 11296808*x^4 + 3415920*x^5 + 488130*x^6 + 31860*x^7 + 755*x^8)*exp(x)/5760. (End)
%e A393842 The first formula given above adds the counts of 8 subsets that are categorized by number of nonzero rows and columns (with transpositions in the same category).
%e A393842 For n=4, a(4) = 67950*0 + 70200*0 + 10260*0 + 360*0 + 2*0 + 11400*0 + 1680*0 + 36*1 = 36.
%e A393842 For n=5, a(5) = 67950*0 + 70200*0 + 10260*0 + 360*0 + 2*0 + 11400*1 + 1680*5 + 36*5^2 = 20700.
%e A393842 For n=6, a(6) = 67950*1 + 70200*1*6 + 10260*1*15 + 360*1*20 + 2*1*15 + 11400*6^2 + 1680*6*15 + 36*15^2 = 1219980.
%e A393842 See Diagram of Subsets for 12 1's. The coefficient 67950 is for the case of two 1's in column/row, no odd, see A001499(6).
%o A393842 (BASIC) 'For Coefficients of Formulas, not the sequence terms. See Link.
%Y A393842 Cf. A001499, A000537, A179058, A396317, A179063, A396321.
%K A393842 nonn,easy,new
%O A393842 1,4
